  "prompt": "Why astronauts have a white and an orange-coloured space suit?",
  "response": "Astronauts wear different colored space suits for specific purposes related to safety and functionality. \n\n1. **White Space Suits**: The white space suits, known as Extravehicular Mobility Units (EMUs), are primarily used for spacewalks (extravehicular activities, or EVAs). The white color reflects sunlight and helps keep the astronaut cool in the extreme temperatures of space. The suit provides life support, mobility, and protection against micrometeorites and radiation.\n\n2. **Orange Space Suits**: The orange suits, known as Advanced Crew Escape Suits (ACES), are primarily used during launch and re-entry. The bright orange color is highly visible, which can be crucial in search and rescue operations if an emergency occurs. Additionally, these suits are designed to provide protection to astronauts in the event of cabin depressurization and are worn during the time the astronauts are in the spacecraft before takeoff and after landing.\n\nIn summary, the different colors and designs serve functional roles for the diverse environments astronauts face in space and during launches and landings.",
